<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-011-068 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 503 534</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 18 1991 v8 n46 p181(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Taligent plans aggressive push for Pink OS. (Pink operatingsystem, an IBM-Apple joint venture)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Freedman, Beth.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Taligent, an IBM-Apple joint venture, plans a campaign to marketits new operating system, which is under development.andP;  Thesoftware, based on an Apple project code-named Pink, is expectedin 1992 or 1993.andP;  It will be an object-oriented product that willbe portable, making it easy for software developers to buildapplications compatible with various companies' hardware.andO;Implementations of the OS will show up for the PowerPCreduced-instruction-set computing platform and for existingplatforms such as the Motorola 68000 and Intel X86 families ofmicroprocessors.andP;  Taligent will market through resellingagreements and will sell a shrink-wrapped version of its own.andP;  Inother Taligent news, David Liddle, considered the top candidatefor CEO of the company, will accept a job at IBM.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Joint ventures)Apple Computer Inc. (Joint ventures)Taligent Inc. (Planning).andO;Ticker:    AAPL; IBM.andO;Topic:     Joint VentureOperating systemsMarketing StrategyStrategic PlanningProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Beth FreedmanandM;As part of a full-scale campaign to launch its operating system, IBM andApple Computer Inc.'s jointly owned Taligent is considering reselleragreements as well as selling its own shrink-wrapped version of the product.andM;Following a course insiders liken to Microsoft Corp.'s business model forMS-DOS, Taligent will also aggressively pursue a host of hardware makers toresell its upcoming object-oriented operating system and tool set, accordingto Edward Birss, a senior Apple vice president charged with managingday-to-day operations at the new firm.andM;&quot;We're looking at all opportunities to make product available --shrink-wrapped software, resellers, as well as trying to anticipate channelsfor system software in the mid-'90s,&quot; Birss said.andM;The Taligent offering -- which is well under way, but not expected to bereleased for another year or two -- is being designed as a portable systemthat will let software developers build a single application that will run ondiverse hardware, Birss said.andP;  The software is based almost entirely onApple's 3-year-old Pink project, and the development team comes primarilyfrom the Cupertino, Calif., company, sources said.andP;  Because Taligent isfollowing an object-oriented course, the carrot for developers will be theease with which they can customize applications to tap the horsepower ofspecific hardware, according to Birss.andM;&quot;[Developers] can add value on top of the system by replacing implementations[of OS modules] with those that offer better performance and by expandingclass libraries,&quot; he explained.andP;  &quot;But it is our intent to make it possiblefor ISVs to build one application that will run across all platformsprovided.&quot;andM;Developers can expect to see implementations of Taligent's operating systemfor the new PowerPC RISC platform embraced by both Apple and IBM as well asfor existing platforms such as Motorola's 68000 family and the Intel X86line, he said.andM;While Taligent product development moves forward inside Apple, formation ofthe Taligent company is in flux.andP;  Birss said the board of the directors forTaligent has not been named yet, and IBM and Apple are frantically searchingfor a CEO.andM;Last week, David Liddle, the widely rumored top candidate for the job,accepted a newly created position at IBM.andP;  Liddle, who founded both MetaphorComputer Systems Inc. and Patriot Partners, will serve as vice president ofnew systems business development at IBM, reporting to Joseph Guglielmi, IBMvice president and general manager of marketing and business development forpersonal systems.andM;Liddle took himself out of the running because the Pink project was far alongand he views himself as more of a crusader, he said.andP;  &quot;Taligent is verymature -- it's following a vision based on Pink, and I've always worked onstuff far in advance.&quot; Others say Liddle got fed up with the intensepoliticking that resulted from an outsider trying to step into anApple-directed effort.andP;  Regardless, IBM and Apple must appoint someoneappropriate for the crucial job in the next few months, observers said.andO;&quot;From the start, the problem of who's going to run Taligent is one of thetime bombs of the alliance,&quot; said Jeffrey Tarter, editor of Softletter, aWatertown, Mass., industry newsletter.andP;  &quot;Operating systems are religion, andyou can't have a religious movement without a messiah.&quot;andM;Liddle will help define IBM's strategy for the Taligent products, determiningwhat pieces to license and how to weave the technology into IBM's operatingsystems, IBM officials said.andP;  Liddle will also handle IBM's strategicoperating systems alliances, working with partners such as Go Corp. andBorland International Inc. as well as cultivating similar relationships withnew parties.andO;</TEXT></DOC>